<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="38">Taxon classification Animalia Coleoptera Lycidae</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="38" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="38">
<taxonomicName LSID="http://zoobank.org/53AA2216-605A-4A64-A10B-C58AEF0B8E31" authority="Pic, 1921" authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1921" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Platerodrilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platerodrilus foliaceus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="foliaceus">Platerodrilus foliaceus</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="9" pageNumber="38">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
Figs 4, 22, 40, 46-47
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="38" type="material examined">
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="38">Material examined.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="38">
Holotype. Male (LMBC, UPOL 000589), Borneo, Central Kalimantan Prov., 60 km SE Muara Teweh, 
<geoCoordinate direction="south" orientation="latitude" precision="15" value="-1.3402778">1°20'25&quot;S</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate direction="east" orientation="longitude" precision="15" value="115.33778">115°20'16&quot;E</geoCoordinate>
, 24.-28. Jun. 2001, 150 m. Paratypes. 12 females, same locality data (LMBC, UPOL 000588).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="38" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="38">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="38">
<taxonomicName authority="Pic, 1921" authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1921" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Platerodrilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platerodrilus foliaceus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="foliaceus">Platerodrilus foliaceus</taxonomicName>
belongs to the 
<taxonomicName authority="Pic, 1921" authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1921" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Platerodrilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platerodrilus paradoxus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paradoxus">Platerodrilus paradoxus</taxonomicName>
group and the male resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Pic, 1921" authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1921" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Platerodrilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platerodrilus paradoxus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paradoxus">Platerodrilus paradoxus</taxonomicName>
in general appearance. 
<taxonomicName authority="Pic, 1921" authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1921" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Platerodrilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platerodrilus foliaceus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="foliaceus">Platerodrilus foliaceus</taxonomicName>
differs in the rounded apex of parameres (Figs 46-47). The female larvae of 
<taxonomicName authority="Pic, 1921" authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1921" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Platerodrilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platerodrilus foliaceus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="foliaceus">Platerodrilus foliaceus</taxonomicName>
are very flat and have much slenderer lateral processes of abdominal segments than 
<taxonomicName authority="Pic, 1921" authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1921" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Platerodrilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platerodrilus paradoxus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paradoxus">Platerodrilus paradoxus</taxonomicName>
(Figs 34, 40).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="39" pageId="9" pageNumber="38" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="38">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="38">Male. Body small-sized, brown, head, antennae, legs except bases of femora and apical three fifths of elytra dark brown (Fig. 4). Head small, with hemispherically prominent eyes, head with eyes slightly wider than frontal margin of pronotum, eye diameter 1.7 times frontal interocular distance. Antennae compressed, covered with long, erected, dense pubescence, length of antennomere 3 0.7 times antennomere 2. Pronotum flat, without carinae, 1.7 times wider than long at midline, frontal margin slightly projected anteriorly, frontal angles obtuse, but apparent, lateral margins rounded, posterior margin slightly bisinuate (Fig. 22). Elytra flat, parallel-sided, elytral costae inconspicuous, elytra 2.9 times longer than width at humeri. Legs slender, compressed, densely pubescent. Male genitalia with robust parameres, phallus slightly curved with bulbous tip. Parameres stout with hooked tip, apical half of ventral edge serrate. Phallobase wide, deeply emarginate (Figs 46-47).</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="39">
<pageBreakToken pageId="10" pageNumber="39" start="start">Female</pageBreakToken>
larva. Body extremely flat and wide (Fig. 40), pronotum triangular, without any glabrous tubercles, in middle of anterior margin four subequal tubercles; mesothorax strongly transverse, with rounded lateral margins and moderately projected posterior angles, metathorax similar in shape with more acutely projected posterior margins. Abdomen with very slender and long lateral processes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="39" type="measurements">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="39">Measurements.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="39">Male. BL 6.0 mm, PL 0.9 mm, PW 1.5 mm, HW 1.7 mm, Edist 0.78 mm, Ediam 0.46 mm. Larva. BL 19.3 mm, PL 5.1 mm, PW 11.2 mm.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="39" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="39">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="39">Indonesia: Kalimantan. Known only from the type locality.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="39" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="39">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="39">The specific epithet refers to the flat body shape of the female larva.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="39" type="remark">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="39">Remark.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="39">The males and female larvae were identified as conspecific on the basis of highly similar sequences of rrnL (Fig. 1).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
